  "text": "TNF-a is a critical early cytokine required for neutrophil recruitment during pneumococcal pneumonia [CITATION_1] . Expression was increased 24 and 48 hours after infection, and the level was sustained to a much greater extent at 48 hours in the gp91 phox2/-mice ( Table 1) . Critical CXC chemokines associated with increased TNF-a expression and neutrophil chemotaxis during pneumococcal infection of the lung, KC (CXCL1) and MIP-2 (CXCL2) [CITATION_2] , were also increased ( Table 1) . As previously reported, MIP-2 production peaked before KC production [CITATION_3] . Because monocyte-derived chemokines such as MCP-1 (CCL2) can amplify neutrophil recruitment in the lung, MCP-1 expression was also investigated and enhanced levels of expression were noted, particularly at later time points after infection, in gp91 phox2/-mice relative to wild-type mice (Table 1) . There was also a significant increase in the amount of IL-6, a pleiotropic cytokine, in BAL from the gp91 phox2/-mice and the level of expression was sustained for 48 hours (Table 1) . These observed increases were seen despite reduced numbers of bacteria in the lungs of gp91 phox2/-mice and were not observed for all cytokines investigated; there was no difference in levels of IL-12 (Table 1) Decreased Neutrophil Apoptosis in gp91 phox2/-Mice Impaired NADPH oxidase function in activated neutrophils is associated with reduced apoptosis induction [CITATION_4] . Levels of apoptosis were estimated in BAL 24 and 48 hours postinfection. Cytospins from BAL showed a reduction in apoptosis in gp91 phox2/-mice compared with C57BL/6 mice ( Figures 5A-5C ). Levels of neutrophil and macrophage apoptosis were also examined by annexin-V/TO-PRO-3 staining and flow cytometry, with the separate cell populations determined by forward/ side scatter characteristics and Ly6G staining to identify neutrophils. There was a significant reduction in annexin-V-PE 1 / TO-PRO-3 2 apoptotic neutrophils (Figures 5D and 5E), with a similar difference when dual annexin-V-PE 1 /TO-PRO-3 1 cells were studied (data not shown). Similarly, there were reduced levels of apoptosis as assessed by Ly6G 1 /Hoechst 1 neutrophils, which persisted for at least 48 hours postinfection (see Figure  E2 ). Macrophage apoptosis was not significantly different between the two strains of mice postinfection (see Figure E3 ).",
